{ Black has a comfortable position thanks to
White's doubled g-pawns. If the g3-pawn were
on h2, then White could play f4, meeting ... Ng4
with h3, after which a central breakthrough by
e5 would be possible. As it is, f4 is well met by
... Ng4, since it would then be hard to dislodge
the knight from g4. Nevertheless, Black must
find a way to improve his position. The first step
is always to see what your opponent is intending.
Here, given a couple of tempi, White will play
Be2 followed by f4 and Bf3, greatly improving
his position. Black must take action against this
plan and he does so by taking the initiative himself on the kingside. }
1... h5! 2. Qd2 (2. Be2 h4 3. f4? hxg3! 4. fxe5 Qh4 5. Bf3 Rxe5 { with two pawns and
a dangerous attack for the piece (the immediate
threat is ... g5-g4). It often happens that the execution of a strategic plan depends on a tactical
point. } { [%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4] }) 2... h4 3. Qf4 { White intends to meet ... hxg3 by Qxg3, when
f4 will again be possible. However, the position
of the queen gives Black the chance to hold up
f4 more or less permanently } 3... g5! 4. Qe3 hxg3 5. Qxg3 Qf6 { The prospects for playing f4 become more
and more distant, especially as Black can play
... Ng6. The only real downside to Black's plan
is that it weakens f5, but a knight arriving there (which can only happen after several preparatory moves) can be exchanged by ... Bc8 and
...Bxf5 } 6. Re3 { Given time, White will play Be2, Rf1 and
again f4. Up to now, Black's play has been defensive, but now he has the chance to take the
initiative himself. } 6... Kf8 { The plan is to move the king to e7 or d7 and
bring the rooks to the kingside, again preventing f4 and starting a kingside attack of his own. } 7. b4 c4 8. Ne2 { heading for f5 } (8. a4 { this move is met with } 8... g4 9. axb5 Ke7 10. bxa6 Bxa6 11. b5 Bc8 { foloowed by ...Rh8 and the black with a decisive attack }) 8... Ke7 9. Nd4 Rh8 10. Nf5+ Kd7 11. Rc3 Kc7 12. Qe3 Bc8 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gc8f5] } 13. f3? (13. Ng3 { is the only chance. although Black
keeps a large advantage after } 13... g4 14. Rdc1 Qh4 15. Bd3 Bd7 16. Bc2 Ng6 { [%csl Gh4,Gg2][%cal Gh4h2,Gg6h4,Gh4g2] }) 13... Bxf5 14. exf5 Qxf5 15. Rd4 Qb1 { Black makes things unnecessarily tricky.
Simply } (15... Qh7 16. Qxg5 f5 17. Kf2 Rag8 18. Qe3 Qg7 { gives him winning attack }) 16. Qxg5 Rag8 17. Qe7+ Kc8 18. Rd2?? Rh1+ 19. Kxh1 Qxf1+ 20. Kh2 Rh8+ 21. Kg3 Qe1+ 22. Rf2 Rg8+ { and it's mate in few moves } *


