{ Assessing this position is not easy, and the
grandmasters watching the game had sharply
diverging opinions about its evaluation. The
most notable feature is the buried bishop on
a1, which is doing little at the moment. Balanced against this, Black's own bishop isn't
exactly bursting with activity, while White's
other pieces are all well placed. On balance,
the position is roughly level, but some GMs
thought that the position should favours Black,
since there's no obvious solution to the problem of the a1-bishop }
1... g5? { Except if Black creates one! This is a good
example of the disastrous consequences of
playing actively when the position isn't strong
enough to support it. Black hopes to play ... g4,
chasing away the knight, and then ... Qc6, but
the line-up of the a1-bishop and the king on h8
should have rung a warning bell.
Black should continue more modestly by Reb8 } (1... Reb8 { aiming to exchange or displace the
active rook on b7. } 2. Qb1 (2. Rcb2 Rxb7 3. Rxb7 Qc6 { also possible }) 2... Rxb7 3. Qxb7 Rb8 4. Qa7 Rb1 5. Bb2 Qe6 6. h3 Nb6) 2. e4 { white doesn't miss the chance to exploit the
weakening of the long diagonal. } { [%csl Gh8,Gf6,Gb2,Gc3,Gd4,Ge5,Gg7,Ga1] } 2... dxe3 { en passant is the best choice } (2... Ne7? { allows the
attractive finish } 3. Rxc5!! Qxc5 4. Bxd4 Qc6 5. Nxg5! Qxb7 6. Bxf6+ Bg7 7. Bxg7+ Kxg7 8. Qf7+ Kh6 9. Qxh7+ Kxg5 10. Qg7+ Ng6 11. f4+ Kh5 12. g4+ Kxg4 13. Qxg6+ Kxf4 14. Qg3#) (2... Re7?! 3. Qb1 Rae8 { Black sets
the trap for exd5? } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gb7b5,Gc2c5,Gb5c5] } 4. exd5?? g4 5. Rxe7 gxf3+ 6. Kxf3 Rxe7) 3. Nxg5 Kg8? { Black should play Nf4+ } (3... Nf4+ 4. Kg1 (4. gxf4 Qc6+ 5. Kg3 Qxb7 6. Bxf6+ Bg7 7. Nf7+ Kg8 8. Nd6+ Qb3 9. Nxe8 Rxe8 10. Bxg7 Qxa2 11. Rxa2 Kxg7 { this position is deadly draw }) 4... exf2+ 5. Rxf2 Re1+ 6. Rf1 Rxf1+ 7. Kxf1 Qxd3+ 8. Kf2 Qd5 9. Qxd5 Nxd5 { when he still has good drawing chances. }) 4. Ne4? { Missing the instantly decisive Rb6 } (4. Rb6 Qxb6 5. Qxd5+ Kh8 6. Rb2 Qa6 7. Rb7 Re7 8. Rxe7 Bxe7 9. Qe4 { [%csl Gh7,Gf7][%cal Ge4h7,Gh7f7] }) 4... Qe6 5. Rd7?! { White can reach a very favourable ending by } { [%cal Gc5c4,Gd3c4,Ge6d7,Ge4f6,Gd5f6] } (5. Bxf6 exf2 6. Rxf2 Ne3+ 7. Kf3 Qxa2 8. Rxa2 Nd5 9. Bg5) 5... Rad8? { This loses at once. The only move is ...c4
White retains an advantage due
to the activity of his bishop on the long diagonal, but Black can still hope to defend. } (5... c4! { to block the queen from d5 square } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc2c4,Ga2d5] } 6. Rxc4 Be7 7. Rb7 Rab8 8. Rxb8 Rxb8 9. Qe2) 6. Rxd5 Qxd5 7. Qxd5+ Rxd5 8. Nxf6+ Kf7 9. Nxd5 e2 10. Bc3 e1=Q 11. Bxe1 Rxe1 12. Nc3 Ra1 13. Nxa4 Rxa3 14. Nxc5 { 1-0 } *


