[UTCTime "10:00:05"]

{ There are_ various ways of creating a plan,
but one of the most common is by analogy. A
knowledge of the plans available in similar positions may suggest one which can be transferred to the situation on the board. Often the
key factor is the pawn-structure; if this is similar to or the same as a known position, it may
well be possible to adapt a plan.
This position arose from a Queen's Indian,
but the pawn-structure is the same as in the
Modem Benoni. White has a central pawn majority, and his main plan is based on playing
e4-eS. This may be reinforced by pieces, for example by Bf4, or it may be supported with f4.
Black must try to keep control of e5 to prevent
White's advance. At this stage the chances are
roughly balanced. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4e5] }
1. e4 Ng4 (1... Qb6 { [%cal Gb5b4] } 2. h3 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gf6g4,Gh3g4] } 2... Rac8 3. Be3 Qb7 4. Bf1! { favours White. He has prevented ... b4 while
Black must worry about Bf4 or a4. }) 2. h3 { A perfectly natural plan, which allows White
to force through f4 as support for an eventual eS. } 2... Nge5 3. Nxe5 Nxe5 4. f4 Nd7?! { Although this retains control of e5, the
knight is not actively placed on d7. } (4... Nc4 { is
better, as White cannot play
The knight on c4
makes it hard for White to develop his c 1-
bishop, so he should probably go in for 5 e5 } 5. b3?? { The knight on c4
makes it hard for White to develop his c 1-
bishop, so he should probably go in for 5 e5 } (5. e5 dxe5 6. b3 Nd6 7. fxe5 Re8 8. Bf4 g5 { the position is totally unclear. }) 5... Bd4+ 6. Kh2 Qa5 { win for bkack }) 5. Be3 { With the knight on d7, White has no trouble
completing his development. } 5... Rc8 6. Kh2 { White keeps his rook on al for the moment,
thereby preventing ... b4 due to the unprotected
bishop on a6. The bishop is not usually placed
here in the analogous line of the Modem Benoni,
and White takes advantage of this factor to hold
up Black's queenside play. Analogies are never
perfect and it's important to check the impact of
any differences. } 6... h5? { The natural 6... Re8 is much better. After
the move played, White can again find the correct plan by analogy with the Modem Benoni.
In lines of the Benoni involving f4, White often sacrifices a pawn by means of e5, meeting
...dxe5 with f5. The same idea is very effective
here; White clears e4 for his pieces, creates a
passed d-pawn and blocks in the g7-bishop.
Note that 6... h5? then proves a serious weakening of Black's kingside, since after White plays
fS he will already be threatening to take on g6. } 7. e5 dxe5 8. f5 Qb6 9. Qf2?! { missing d6 } (9. d6 Qxd6 10. Rad1 Qe7 11. fxg6 { with a winning attack; for example } 11... Nf6 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 { and f7 collapses. }) 9... Qf6 10. Ne4 Qxf5 11. Qe2 Nb6 12. Nxc5 Rxc5 13. Bxc5 Rd8 14. Rad1 Nc4?! { Qd7 offers more resistance. } 15. Be7 Re8 16. d6 Bc8 17. b3 Nb6 18. Qxb5 Bd7 19. Qf1 Qe6 20. a4 a5 21. b4 axb4 22. a5 Na4 23. Bd5 Qf5 24. Qg2 Rc8 25. Rf1 Qc2 26. Rd2 Qc3 27. Rxf7 Kh8 28. Bg5 Nc5 29. Rc2 { 1-0 } *


