[FEN "r2r2k1/p1q1npbp/n1p3p1/1p2p3/3PP1b1/2P2NP1/P1N1QPBP/R1B1R1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.08.14"]
[UTCTime "12:33:43"]

{ In the middlegame, a central pawn is generally more effective than a flank pawn. Here
White has an advantage thanks to his extra central pawn and Black's poorly-placed a6-knight,
which has few active prospects. }
1... exd4 2. cxd4 { Black gives up his foothold in the centre in
the hope that his pressure on the long dark diagonal will enable him to break up White's pawn
duo on d4 and e4. } 2... c5 3. Bf4 Qd7 4. d5! { This refutes Black's idea. White intends to
keep his central pawns even at the cost of the exchange. If Black takes on aI, he will not only
have to cope with White's pawns, but in addition
his kingside will be exposed } 4... c4 { Black hopes to activate his a6-knight by Nc5-d3 } { [%cal Ga6c5,Gc5d3] } (4... Bxa1 5. Rxa1 c4 6. d6 Nc6 7. a4 bxa4 8. Qxc4 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 g5 10. Bxg5 Ne5 11. Qe2 Nc5 12. Be7 { with a clear advantage for White. }) 5. Qe3 { An excellent response, not only unpinning
the f3-knight and thereby threatening Ne5,
but also preventing Black's ...Nc5 idea. } 5... Bxf3 { Black is forced to make this exchange to stop
Ne5, but now he faces new problems on the
long light diagonal. } 6. Bxf3 b4?! { Black's queens ide pawns are far less effective than White's central pawn-mass. Central
pawns are better because they are more likely
to attack enemy pieces as they advance, and
because the advance of central pawns very often leads to an attack on the enemy king } (6... Bxa1 7. Rxa1 f6 8. Qc3 Rf8 9. Qa3 Qb7 10. Rb1 { White's numerous advantages
(two bishops, passed d-pawn, knight penetrating to d4 and then c6 or e6) are worth far more
than Black's extra exchange. }) 7. Rab1 { Avoiding the bishop's attack, and gaining
time by threatening the b4-pawn. } 7... Qa4 8. Nd4 Nc5 { The knight finally escapes from a6, but it's
too late as White's central pawns are ready to
advance. } 9. d6 Nd3 10. e5 { This multi-purpose move blocks the long
dark-square diagonal and so threatens to take
on e7, and also opens the f3-bishop's diagonal
to attack the rook on as. } 10... Nxe1 11. Rxe1 { Black is temporarily the exchange up, but the
central pawns give White a winning position. } 11... Nf5 12. Nxf5 gxf5 13. Bxa8 Rxa8 14. e6 { A devastating move; Black cannot take, since
... fxe6 29 Qxe6+ Kh8 30 d7 followed by
Qe8+ leads to a forced mate, so the pawns roll
on unopposed. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf7e6,Ge3e6,Gg8h8,Gd6d7] } *


