[UTCTime "14:06:35"]

{ Even a single extra central pawn can confer
an advantage, although this may be slight.
Here the position is close to equality, but White
retains an edge thanks to his e-pawn. It's posªsible that Black's queenside pawns would play
a significant role in the endgame, but in the
middlegame White's central majority is a more
important factor, not only because it offers
more influence and space in the centre, but
also because it could provide the foundation
for an attack against Black's slightly weakened kingside }
1. Rfe1 Rad8 2. Bf1 { White envisages moving his knight from f3
and starting an attack by pushing his f-pawn;
this modest move(Bf1) removes the bishop from attack after a possible ... Nd4. } 2... Bf7 3. Nh2 { If White is given time, a combination of Ng4
and f4-f5 would generate real kingside threats. } { [%cal Gh2g4,Gf2f4,Gf4f5] } 3... Be6 { Black's bishop returns to e6, ready to take
the knight if it jumps to g4. The problem is that
if White manages to force through f4-f5, the
bishop will have to move again, costing time } 4. f4 Nd4? { A serious error, allowing White to play f5
without a fight. From a purely visual perspective, the knight looks actively placed on d4, but
in fact it achieves little there and is unable to
join in the defence of the threatened kingside. } (4... Rfe8 { this move is far more purposeful, preventing f5,
at least for the moment, since } 5. f5? { simply
loses a pawn after } 5... Bxf5 { [%csl Ge3][%cal Ge7e3] }) 5. f5 Bf7 (5... gxf5?? 6. exf5 { black loses a piece } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ge3e7,Gf5e6] }) 6. Ng4 gxf5 { This is obviously risky, but Black didn't have
a better move. White threatened to step up the
pressure by Qh6, when a breakthrough by e5
would be in the air. Thanks to the bad position
of the knight on d4, Black no longer has the
possibility of ... Ne5 to swap off White's dangerous g4-knight. } (6... Nc6 7. Ne2 Ne5 8. Nh6+ Kg7 9. Nxf7 Kxf7 10. Nf4 { Black suffers from the terrible weakness of the e6-square } { [%csl Ge6] }) 7. Nh6+ Kh8 (7... Kg7 8. Qxd4 Kxh6 9. exf5 Rxd4 10. Rxe7 Rd7 11. Rxd7 Nxd7 12. Ne4 { gives White
a very favourable ending. }) 8. Qf2 fxe4?? { A blunder losing at once } 9. Rxe4 Qd6 10. Rd1 c5 11. Nxf7+ Rxf7 12. b4 f5 13. bxc5 fxe4 14. Qxf7 Nf3+ 15. Qxf3 exf3 16. cxd6 { 1-0 } *


[Event "strategy: improving peace position"]
