[ChapterName "improving peace position"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/CPQpMKcx/Hh0FVVt8"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/pawnsacrifice97"]
[FEN "r1qn2k1/3bb2p/r2p1pp1/pp1Pp3/1Pp1P3/P1P4P/1BB1QPPK/R3RN2 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.12.09"]
[UTCTime "14:21:55"]

{ Many plans involve improving the activity of
a single piece. This position is close to equality,
with Black's main asset being his pressure along
the a-file. White always wants to meet ... axb4
with axb4 because playing cxb4 would leave
White with a backward a-pawn and Black with a
protected passed c-pawn. Thus the a-file pressure prevents White from activating his b2-
bishop by Bc1-e3, since Bcl would be met by
... axb4. Although White's movements are a little
restricted, he isn't under any real pressure, so
Black must find a plan to improve his position. A
good start is to look for a piece that isn't doing
much and see if it can be moved to a more active
square. Here both the d8-knight and the e7-
bishop aren't pulling their weight, so Black focuses on transferring them to better squares.
Playing ... Bf8-h6 is a perfectly reasonable idea,
but Black decides on the equally good plan of
... Nf7 followed by ... Bd8-b6. }
1... Nf7 2. Ne3?! { Here and over the next few moves, White
adopts the wrong plan. He aims for kingside
play based on f4, but it's hard for this to achieve
anything when Black has a firm grip on e5 } (2. bxa5 Rxa5 3. Ne3 { is correct, aiming for a4 and
the liquidation of the pawns on the a- and b-files.
In this case, Black's a-file pressure is nullified
and an exchange of all the rooks is very likely. }) 2... Bd8 3. Rf1 Bb6 4. Rae1 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gf4f5] } 4... Kg7 5. Bb1 axb4 6. axb4 { White has conceded the a-file, so Black may
as well swap pawns. Although he cannot penetrate with a rook at the moment, White's bishops are tied down to covering al and a2. } 6... Qe8 { To meet f4 with ... exf4 Rxf4 Qe5. } 7. g3?! { Preparing f4, but weakening the h3-pawn. } 7... Qc8! { Forcing an awkward decision. } 8. g4?! { After this White is in real trouble. h4 is
better, although after ... h5 followed by ... Nh6
White will be in no position to play f4 due to the
resulting weakness of g4. } 8... Bxe3 { Black's plan has succeeded: his bad bishop
from e7 is exchanged for an active white knight. } 9. fxe3 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Ge3f4] } (9. Qxe3 { is met by another plan based on improving the position of a piece: } 9... g5 { ... g5 followed by ... Nh8-g6-f4 and eventually ... h5. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gf7h8,Gh8g6,Gg6f4,Gh7h5] }) 9... Qd8 10. Rf3 Qe7 11. Ref1 Rf8 12. Qg2 { Now ... h5! gives Black a decisive advantage in all lines: } 12... Raa8?! { retaining an edge which he eventually converted into a
win } (12... h5 13. Rg3 (13. gxh5 Ng5 14. Rg3 Rh8 15. Rh1 Rxh5 16. Kg1 Rh4 17. Kf1 Ra8 18. Ke1 Rah8 { Black wins material }) (13. Rxf6 hxg4 14. h4 Qxf6 15. Rxf6 Kxf6 { also winning for black } { [%cal Gf8h8,Gh8h5,Ga6a8,Ga8h8] }) 13... hxg4 14. hxg4 Rh8+ 15. Kg1 Ng5 { followed by bringing the major
pieces to the h-file, leads to a decisive attack for
Black } 16. Kf2 Raa8 17. Rg1 Rh7 18. Rh1 Rxh1 19. Qxh1 Rh8 20. Qg2 Qe8 21. Kg1) *


