1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 c6 7. e3 Be7 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Bd3 Re8 10. h3 Nf8 11. Bf4 a5 12. O-O Ng6 13. Bh2 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Rfe1 Be6 { In positions with this type of Queen's Gambit pawn-structure, White nonnally has only
two possible plans: he can either play for the
central break e4, or he can play a3, Rabl and
b4-bS. Here playing e4 achieves nothing apart
from giving White an isolated d-pawn, so the
balance lies firmly in favour of a queenside advance. Such an advance is called a minority attack because it involves advancing White's two
queenside pawns against Black's three. Black
sometimes meets this plan by generating kingside counterplay, but here this is difficult as the
dark-squared bishops have been exchanged. } 16. a3 Re7 17. Rab1 Rae8 18. b4 axb4 19. axb4 Bd7 20. b5 { The point of White's pawn advance is to
leave Black with a weak queenside pawn; if
Black takes on b5 then he has isolated b- and dpawns, while allowing the exchange bxc6 bxc6
will give Black a backward c-pawn. } 20... Ne4 (20... c5 { It's sometimes possible for Black to meet b5
with ... c5, but here } 21. dxc5 Qxc5 22. Rec1 Rc8 23. Qb2 Qd6 24. Na4 { leaves White with a clear advantage. } { [%cal Gb2d4] }) 21. bxc6 bxc6 22. Rb6 { Black is not only left with a weak pawn, but
in addition White's pieces are very active. By
contrast, Black's bishop is passively placed. } 22... Nxc3 23. Qxc3 Qf6 { Black has no counterplay and is reduced to
the grim defence of a position with few active
prospects. The threat of ... Bxh3 is a pinprick
which causes White no real inconvenience. } 24. Bxg6 { The exchange of this knight eliminates
Black's last prospect of serious kingside play } 24... Qxg6 { [%csl Gh3][%cal Gg6g1,Gd7h3] } (24... hxg6 25. Ne5 Rc8 26. Qc5 { is terrible for Black }) 25. Kf1 (25. Ne5?? Rxe5 26. dxe5 Bxh3 27. Kf1 Qxg2+ 28. Ke2 Bg4+ 29. Kd2 Qxf2+ 30. Kc1 h5 { [%cal Gh5h4,Gh4h3,Gh3h2,Gh2h1,Ge8e6,Ge6h6] }) 25... f6 { lack has managed to keep the knight out of
e5, but c5 is another tempting outpost. } 26. Ra1 Qh5 27. Ne1 Qf5 { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gf5f1,Ge7e3] } 28. Kg1 Qg5 29. Kh2 Qf5 30. Nd3 Qe6 31. Kg1 Rc8 32. Rb7 Rf7 33. Raa7 Be8 34. Qb4 Rd8 35. Nc5 Qc8 36. Qb6 h5 37. Rc7 Rxc7 38. Rxc7 Qa8 39. Ra7 Qc8 40. Rb7 Bf7 41. Qa7 Rf8 42. Nd7 Re8 43. Nxf6+ gxf6 44. Rxf7 Qf5 45. Rg7+ Kh8 46. Qf7 { [%cal Gg7g6,Gf7g7] } *


