1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 8. Be2 Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O c6 12. b4 { has various methods of countering it. One is to meet b4 with ... b5 followed by
playing a knight to b6 and c4; another, which is
used in this game, is to arrange to meet b5 with
... c5. } 12... Re8 13. Qb3 a5 { Black even encourages White to push his b-pawn } 14. b5?! (14. bxa5 Rxa5 15. a4 { better, when White
has some pressure along the b- and c-files. }) 14... c5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rac1 Bxc3?! (16... a4! { is the simplest method of demonstrating that White has achieved nothing from
the opening. After } 17. Nxa4 c4 18. Qc2 Nd7 19. Nc3 Ra3 20. Qd2 Nc5 21. Nd4 Qa5 { with
... Ne6 to come, Black has full compensation
for the pawn. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gc5e6] }) 17. Qxc3 Nd7 18. Rfd1 Qb6 { The minority attack has produced no concrete benefit for White. Black, it is true, has
hanging pawns in the centre but these can just as easily be strong as weak. } 19. Bf1 Rac8 20. h3 Nf6 21. Nd2 c4!? { Dynamic play by Black. He weakens d4, but
restricts White's bishop and opens a diagonal
for his queen. Objectively it is no stronger than
other moves, but it presents White with tricky
problems to solve. } 22. a4 Re6 23. Rc2 Rce8 24. Nf3?! { Taking aim at d4 appears logical, but it allows
Black to develop dangerous piece activity. 24
Nb1 is better, intending Qd4 followed by Nc3. } 24... Ne4 25. Qa1 Rf6 26. Rd4? { This second error allows Black to break open
White's kingside and exploit the undefended
rook on c2 } (26. Nd4 { is more logical, although
even here } 26... Bc8) 26... Rxf3! 27. gxf3 Qg6+ 28. Bg2 (28. Kh1 Ng3+ 29. fxg3 Qxc2) (28. Kh2 Ng5 29. Qd1 Nxf3+ 30. Qxf3 Qxc2 $19) 28... Ng5 29. Rc1 Nxf3+ 30. Kf1 Nh2+ 31. Kg1 Nf3+ 32. Kf1 Nxd4 33. Qxd4 Qf5 { Black has an extra pawn, but his bad bishop
means he still has some work to do to exploit it } 34. Kg1 Re5! 35. Qa7 Qc8 36. Kf1 (36. Qxa5 Rg5 37. Kf1 d4 38. Bxb7 Qxb7 39. Rxc4 Qg2+ 40. Ke2 d3+ { s Black a winning attack }) 36... Rg5 37. Qd4 Qf5 38. f4 Rg6 39. Kf2 Kh7 40. Rd1 Qc2+ 41. Rd2 Qxa4 42. b6 Qb4 43. Rb2 Qe7 44. Ra2 Qh4+ { 0-1 } 45. Ke2 *


