{ Black stands worse thanks to his weak d6- W
pawn, which White can easily attack via the
half-open d-file. White also controls more space,
although this is not very significant as several
minor pieces have already been exchanged. It's
easy to lose a position such as this, since Black
has no obvious counterplay. black, however,
saved the game using two basic ideas that apply
to many inferior positions: finding counterplay,
and reducing the pressure by liquidation. }
1... Be6 { Developing a piece and attacking the c4-
pawn, so that even if White plays Rad1 he will
not immediately be threatening to win a pawn. } 2. b3 { Unavoidable sooner or later, since otherwise
White will never be threatening to take on d6. } 2... a5! { The start of an excellent defensive plan. Black
will meet Radl with ... c5, allowing him to defend the d-pawn by ... Ra6, while the advance of
the pawn to a4 will not only reduce the material
on the board, but also open the a-file for possible later counterplay. Moves such as this may
not get the same plaudits as brilliant sacrifices,
but they are just as instructive. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ga8a6,Ga6d6] } 3. Rad1 c5 { Making the d-pawn permanently backward
may look dreadful, but it's the only way to
avoid losing a pawn. A single weakness is usually not fatal in itself, but Black must ensure that White is not given the time to improve his
position and provoke another weakness somewhere else on the board. } 4. R4d3 a4 5. Qc1 { For the moment White cannot make progress
since the d-pawn can be attacked three times
and defended three times. The only chance for
White to increase his advantage is on the kingside, but preparing any kind of pawn advance
there is clearly going to take some time } 5... h6 6. Qd2 axb3 7. axb3 Ra3 { Black makes use of the open a-file to counter-attack the b3-pawn. } 8. Qb2 { Expelling the rook from a3, but relieving
some of the pressure from d6. It's evident that
White is unable to force Black into the type of
totally passive position necessary to give him
time to make progress on the kingside. } 8... Ra6 9. h4 Rb8! { Another fine defensive move. The pressure is
momentarily off d6, so Black takes the chance to
force through ... b5. } 10. Qd2 b5 { Black has fully equalized since exchanging
on b5 leaves the b3-pawn just as weak as the
one on d6. } 11. Rxd6 Rxd6 12. Qxd6 Qxd6 13. Rxd6 bxc4 14. bxc4 Bxc4 15. Rc6 Re8 16. Rxc5 Bxe2 17. Bxe2 Rxe2 18. Kf1 $10 { 1/2-1/2 } *


